1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,420
So imagine you are standing in the 25th century.

2
00:00:03,820 --> 00:00:11,340
You are stationed on this massive, I mean, just absolutely colossal rotating ring construct.

3
00:00:12,080 --> 00:00:17,500
And it's suspended in orbit right above this violently stormy gas giant.

4
00:00:17,800 --> 00:00:19,860
Wow, that is quite a visual.

5
00:00:20,160 --> 00:00:21,200
Yeah, it's intense.

6
00:00:21,200 --> 00:00:31,860
And inside this colossal piece of engineering, you know, the lifeblood of human survival is basically pumping through these countless mechanical arteries.

7
00:00:32,520 --> 00:00:32,640
Right.

8
00:00:32,780 --> 00:00:34,600
So the air scrubbers are humming.

9
00:00:35,020 --> 00:00:38,220
The shield controls are processing all this telemetry.

10
00:00:38,540 --> 00:00:45,940
The vast administrative bureaucracies are, well, they're processing the lives and deaths of thousands of colonists.

11
00:00:45,960 --> 00:00:47,540
Which is a massive undertaking.

12
00:00:47,700 --> 00:00:48,220
Exactly.

13
00:00:48,220 --> 00:00:50,100
But here is the kicker.

14
00:00:50,100 --> 00:01:01,020
Every single one of these complex mechanisms is running and occasionally failing with complete and utter indifference to the individual human beings inside them.

15
00:01:01,260 --> 00:01:01,980
Indifference, yeah.

16
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:04,920
Like a warning light strobes in a corridor.

17
00:01:05,720 --> 00:01:09,180
A pressure gauge fluctuates in some filtration plant.

18
00:01:09,560 --> 00:01:12,460
A physical stamp falls on a piece of paper in an office.

19
00:01:12,700 --> 00:01:14,460
Just business as usual for the station.

20
00:01:14,840 --> 00:01:15,120
Right.

21
00:01:15,120 --> 00:01:16,720
The station just rotates.

22
00:01:17,260 --> 00:01:17,780
Unhurried.

23
00:01:18,540 --> 00:01:19,100
Consistent.

24
00:01:19,100 --> 00:01:22,080
It doesn't care about your aspirations, you know.

25
00:01:22,240 --> 00:01:23,360
It doesn't care about your fears.

26
00:01:23,600 --> 00:01:25,860
And it certainly doesn't care about your well-being.

27
00:01:26,100 --> 00:01:27,080
Because why would it?

28
00:01:27,460 --> 00:01:27,940
Exactly.

29
00:01:28,320 --> 00:01:29,720
It's only imperative.

30
00:01:29,940 --> 00:01:34,340
It's only recognizable drive is just the continuation of its own operation.

31
00:01:34,900 --> 00:01:35,960
I love that setup.

32
00:01:36,120 --> 00:01:36,360
Yeah.

33
00:01:36,360 --> 00:01:43,120
Because it really, well, it strips away all of our fundamental human-centric arrogance.

34
00:01:43,120 --> 00:01:44,020
Oh, absolutely.

35
00:01:44,620 --> 00:01:51,720
We are so accustomed to viewing the universe as this theater built for our personal dramas.

36
00:01:51,960 --> 00:01:56,040
But that visual completely decenters us.

37
00:01:56,040 --> 00:02:05,260
It places us as mere biological necessities operating within something far larger and honestly entirely alien.

38
00:02:05,260 --> 00:02:10,240
Yeah, that profound sense of systemic indifference is our starting point today.

39
00:02:10,440 --> 00:02:11,760
So welcome to the deep dive.

40
00:02:11,980 --> 00:02:12,440
Glad to be here.

41
00:02:12,800 --> 00:02:15,680
We are exploring a truly fascinating text today.

42
00:02:15,880 --> 00:02:19,960
It's titled Communication.PDF, authored by Fliction.

43
00:02:20,400 --> 00:02:21,680
Such a great piece of work.

44
00:02:21,680 --> 00:02:22,500
It really is.

45
00:02:22,560 --> 00:02:27,460
It's this brilliant synthesis of hard science fiction and actual historical biography.

46
00:02:27,700 --> 00:02:27,820
Right.

47
00:02:28,200 --> 00:02:39,260
So it takes the life and the notoriously dense sociological theories of a real 20th century German thinker named Nicholas Luhmann.

48
00:02:39,540 --> 00:02:39,860
Yes.

49
00:02:39,860 --> 00:02:49,240
And it basically hurls them hundreds of years into the future, spanning a period from, I think, the year 2400 to 2464.

50
00:02:49,420 --> 00:02:51,120
That's the exact timeline, yeah.

51
00:02:51,120 --> 00:02:58,660
So our mission for this deep dive is to dissect the central reality-bending premise of this narrative.

52
00:02:59,020 --> 00:03:01,880
It's a thesis that confronts you right away.

53
00:03:02,180 --> 00:03:06,720
And that thesis is, society is not made of people.

54
00:03:07,080 --> 00:03:08,640
It is made of communication.

55
00:03:09,080 --> 00:03:15,640
That simple sentence just, I mean, it forces a radical rewiring of your basic assumptions about reality.

56
00:03:15,800 --> 00:03:16,540
It really does.

57
00:03:16,540 --> 00:03:24,200
And what makes this source material so compelling is that we aren't dealing with some dry, impenetrable, academic textbook.

58
00:03:24,960 --> 00:03:25,260
Right.

59
00:03:25,440 --> 00:03:26,080
Thank goodness.

60
00:03:26,360 --> 00:03:26,540
Yeah.

61
00:03:27,160 --> 00:03:30,400
We are navigating a highly sensory cinematic narrative.

62
00:03:30,580 --> 00:03:36,600
The author uses the temperature of the lighting, the stark color palettes, the geometry, the architecture.

63
00:03:36,600 --> 00:03:38,560
Oh, the architecture is huge in this.

64
00:03:38,940 --> 00:03:39,300
Exactly.

65
00:03:39,500 --> 00:03:50,060
And this pervasive, underlying mechanical hum in the sound design, all of it is used to manifest complex sociological concepts.

66
00:03:50,560 --> 00:03:52,020
You don't just read the theory.

67
00:03:52,500 --> 00:03:57,960
The environment actually forces you to experience the mechanics of it.

68
00:03:57,960 --> 00:03:58,300
Right.

69
00:03:58,500 --> 00:04:06,940
And to truly grasp a framework this massive, we can't start by looking at human psychology or individual motivations.

70
00:04:07,020 --> 00:04:08,920
No, that would be missing the point entirely.

71
00:04:09,120 --> 00:04:09,380
Yeah.

72
00:04:09,500 --> 00:04:10,840
We have to look at the substrate.

73
00:04:11,280 --> 00:04:18,280
We have to begin with the biological and mechanical systems that sustain life, which is exactly where the narrative opened.

74
00:04:18,380 --> 00:04:19,380
The Lunenberg Station.

75
00:04:19,380 --> 00:04:20,020
Right.

76
00:04:20,180 --> 00:04:28,020
So we are placed on Lunenberg Station in 2410, and we're introduced to a 10-year-old iteration of Lumen.

77
00:04:28,540 --> 00:04:29,100
This is a kid.

78
00:04:29,120 --> 00:04:29,320
Yeah.

79
00:04:29,680 --> 00:04:32,880
And he's standing in this vast fermentation plant.

80
00:04:33,060 --> 00:04:43,160
It's filled with these enormous semi-translucent cylindrical tanks where this green-brown biomass is circulating in slow, unending spirals.

81
00:04:43,240 --> 00:04:45,760
The environmental descriptors here are so crucial.

82
00:04:45,820 --> 00:04:46,700
Oh, tell me about it.

83
00:04:46,700 --> 00:04:50,080
Because nothing in this plant is clean or sharply defined.

84
00:04:50,580 --> 00:04:57,080
The edges of the machinery are soft, suggesting the structure has been reworked, patched, and adapted over generations.

85
00:04:57,480 --> 00:04:59,180
Like it's organic, almost.

86
00:04:59,300 --> 00:04:59,760
Exactly.

87
00:05:00,180 --> 00:05:05,200
And there is a sound, a low, persistent mechanical hum.

88
00:05:05,920 --> 00:05:10,200
It isn't loud, but it vibrates right through the floorboards.

89
00:05:10,400 --> 00:05:13,680
It's basically the sound of existence, a system breathing.

90
00:05:13,940 --> 00:05:14,160
Yeah.

91
00:05:14,160 --> 00:05:29,200
So we watch Lumen's father moving between these massive tanks, checking pressure gauges, and he opens a maintenance panel to reveal this dense, almost chaotic network of tubing and filtration loops.

92
00:05:29,480 --> 00:05:29,700
Right.

93
00:05:29,960 --> 00:05:32,480
And he doesn't overhaul the machine.

94
00:05:32,760 --> 00:05:34,540
He doesn't do a massive repair.

95
00:05:34,740 --> 00:05:37,680
He just nudges a single valve, a half turn.

96
00:05:37,680 --> 00:05:41,720
And he says to his son, it keeps itself going.

97
00:05:41,820 --> 00:05:42,740
You just correct it.

98
00:05:43,060 --> 00:05:48,620
That singular line is, well, it's the cornerstone for the entire philosophical edifice that follows.

99
00:05:48,760 --> 00:05:49,140
Definitely.

100
00:05:49,500 --> 00:05:54,000
To understand why we have to look closely at the concept of autopoiesis.

101
00:05:54,140 --> 00:05:54,400
Okay.

102
00:05:54,420 --> 00:05:55,200
Let's get into that.

103
00:05:55,200 --> 00:06:03,220
So it's a term originally coined in the 1970s by two Chilean biologists, Humberto Maturana and Francisco Varela.

104
00:06:03,560 --> 00:06:04,520
Maturana and Varela.

105
00:06:04,660 --> 00:06:04,780
Yep.

106
00:06:05,240 --> 00:06:10,760
The word comes from the Greek auto, meaning self, and poiesis, meaning creation or production.

107
00:06:10,940 --> 00:06:11,640
Self-creation.

108
00:06:11,640 --> 00:06:12,240
Exactly.

109
00:06:12,420 --> 00:06:16,000
They were trying to define what makes something biologically alive.

110
00:06:16,140 --> 00:06:16,320
Oh.

111
00:06:16,600 --> 00:06:28,020
And they concluded that a living system, like, say, a single biological cell, is a machine that constantly produces the very components that make up the machine.

112
00:06:28,180 --> 00:06:28,420
Right.

113
00:06:28,540 --> 00:06:29,540
So it builds itself.

114
00:06:29,780 --> 00:06:30,040
Yes.

115
00:06:30,760 --> 00:06:38,200
The cell's membrane defines its boundary against the environment, and the chemical processes inside maintain that boundary.

116
00:06:38,320 --> 00:06:39,480
It keeps itself going.

117
00:06:39,480 --> 00:06:44,260
So the cell isn't trying to, like, change the world or do anything grand.

118
00:06:44,360 --> 00:06:48,380
It's just trying to maintain the conditions required for it to remain a cell.

119
00:06:48,720 --> 00:06:49,200
Precisely.

120
00:06:49,500 --> 00:06:51,660
It is a closed loop of self-production.

121
00:06:52,620 --> 00:07:03,460
Now, the real Nicholas Luhmann took this concept from cellular biology and performed one of the most audacious intellectual leaps of the 20th century.

122
00:07:03,720 --> 00:07:05,180
This is the crazy part.

123
00:07:05,220 --> 00:07:06,020
It really is.

124
00:07:06,020 --> 00:07:11,480
He argued that human social systems operate on the exact same biological principle.

125
00:07:11,480 --> 00:07:12,080
Wow.

126
00:07:12,080 --> 00:07:18,980
The economy, the legal system, science, politics, they're all autopoietic systems.

127
00:07:19,180 --> 00:07:20,040
They're closed loops.

128
00:07:20,380 --> 00:07:22,040
They don't exist to serve humanity.

129
00:07:22,700 --> 00:07:24,940
They exist to continuously reproduce themselves.

130
00:07:24,940 --> 00:07:28,020
That is, I mean, that's heavy.

131
00:07:28,540 --> 00:07:28,940
Very.

132
00:07:29,280 --> 00:07:38,260
And what's fascinating here is how, in that wide shot in the fermentation plant, the framing of the scene explicitly illustrates this.

133
00:07:38,340 --> 00:07:38,660
Right.

134
00:07:38,980 --> 00:07:41,640
The machinery fills the entire visual field.

135
00:07:42,020 --> 00:07:44,020
The human figures are swallowed by it.

136
00:07:44,020 --> 00:07:53,060
The script explicitly notes that they are inside the system, serving as the biological substrate, but they are not at its center.

137
00:07:53,280 --> 00:07:53,680
Right.

138
00:07:53,880 --> 00:07:55,380
They are just parts of the machine.

139
00:07:55,760 --> 00:07:59,040
And the 10-year-old boy realizes this instinctively.

140
00:07:59,180 --> 00:07:59,960
He really does.

141
00:07:59,980 --> 00:08:02,380
Like, he isn't watching his father's face.

142
00:08:02,820 --> 00:08:05,760
He isn't marveling at the sheer volume of the biomass.

143
00:08:06,260 --> 00:08:09,440
He is watching the relations between the instruments.

144
00:08:09,440 --> 00:08:12,700
Which is such a strange thing for a 10-year-old to do.

145
00:08:13,320 --> 00:08:22,480
When a needle on a gauge spikes and then slowly drifts back down to a stable baseline on its own, he doesn't see a mechanical fix.

146
00:08:22,920 --> 00:08:23,860
He sees behavior.

147
00:08:24,340 --> 00:08:29,920
He sees a system reacting to an internal disturbance and reestablishing its own equilibrium.

148
00:08:30,540 --> 00:08:34,380
He is learning to see the invisible architecture of relations.

149
00:08:34,600 --> 00:08:35,120
Exactly.

150
00:08:35,120 --> 00:08:38,840
We see this cognitive evolution crystallize a few years later.

151
00:08:39,440 --> 00:08:44,300
Lumen is now 13, and he's sitting in a standard educational classroom on the station.

152
00:08:44,880 --> 00:08:49,360
This scene perfectly captures that shift in perception.

153
00:08:49,720 --> 00:08:50,540
It's brilliant.

154
00:08:50,900 --> 00:08:56,840
The teacher is speaking at the front of the room, but the narrative completely mutes the content of the lecture.

155
00:08:57,420 --> 00:08:59,460
The words literally do not matter.

156
00:09:00,060 --> 00:09:03,520
The history or the math being taught is entirely irrelevant.

157
00:09:03,900 --> 00:09:05,800
Because the content is just noise.

158
00:09:06,300 --> 00:09:06,900
Exactly.

159
00:09:06,900 --> 00:09:11,500
What young Lumen begins to observe is the structure containing the noise.

160
00:09:11,860 --> 00:09:17,740
He stops looking at the teacher and starts observing the spatial arrangement of the room itself.

161
00:09:18,380 --> 00:09:20,220
The rigid rows of desks.

162
00:09:20,900 --> 00:09:24,320
The uniform direction of the student's physical attention.

163
00:09:24,540 --> 00:09:24,860
Right.

164
00:09:24,860 --> 00:09:32,340
He begins to perceive what are described as vectors pointing forward and the recursive loop of question and response.

165
00:09:33,380 --> 00:09:42,240
For a fleeting moment, the human beings vanish, and the arrangement simplifies into a pure, visible pattern of flow.

166
00:09:42,900 --> 00:09:47,120
The script actually notes it simplifies for like a two-second pattern of flow.

167
00:09:47,120 --> 00:09:53,320
Okay, let's unpack this because I want to make sure we really grasp the magnitude of this perspective shift.

168
00:09:53,440 --> 00:09:54,600
Yeah, it's vital.

169
00:09:54,760 --> 00:09:56,180
Think of a basketball game.

170
00:09:56,220 --> 00:09:56,920
Okay, I'm with you.

171
00:09:57,360 --> 00:09:59,700
Most people watch the superstar players, right?

172
00:09:59,920 --> 00:10:02,060
They watch the individuals shooting the ball.

173
00:10:02,320 --> 00:10:02,880
Of course.

174
00:10:02,880 --> 00:10:06,160
But young Lumen isn't watching the players.

175
00:10:06,380 --> 00:10:07,920
He's watching the passing lanes.

176
00:10:08,340 --> 00:10:12,580
He's watching the offensive plays and the rules of the referee.

177
00:10:13,140 --> 00:10:16,640
He's watching the game itself as an invisible structure.

178
00:10:16,640 --> 00:10:19,460
That is a much more accurate framework.

179
00:10:20,060 --> 00:10:24,120
He is mapping the pathways, completely ignoring the nodes.

180
00:10:24,280 --> 00:10:24,460
Yeah.

181
00:10:24,720 --> 00:10:32,900
And the text notes that he actually begins writing this down, cataloging the structure of the communication rather than taking notes on the lesson.

182
00:10:33,100 --> 00:10:36,960
It is a brilliant display of his emerging genius.

183
00:10:37,180 --> 00:10:42,740
But, you know, observing a quiet, perfectly functioning system is relatively easy.

184
00:10:42,860 --> 00:10:43,160
Sure.

185
00:10:43,160 --> 00:10:51,120
A slow-moving fermentation tank or a highly disciplined classroom naturally lends itself to structural analysis.

186
00:10:51,940 --> 00:10:59,420
Lumen knew, and the narrative demonstrates, that to prove a system is truly autonomous and indifferent to its human components,

187
00:10:59,780 --> 00:11:04,200
you have to look at what it does when it is violently pushed to the brink of destruction.

188
00:11:04,500 --> 00:11:06,720
And we witness exactly that test.

189
00:11:06,780 --> 00:11:07,240
We do.

190
00:11:07,240 --> 00:11:10,300
The narrative advances to the year 2416.

191
00:11:10,300 --> 00:11:16,000
Lumen is 16 years old, assigned to shield control on Lunenberg Station.

192
00:11:16,480 --> 00:11:21,100
And the station is suddenly caught in a massive, catastrophic orbital assault.

193
00:11:21,400 --> 00:11:22,440
It's terrifying.

194
00:11:22,680 --> 00:11:28,520
The atmospheric contrast from the organic warmth of the fermentation plant is just jarring.

195
00:11:28,840 --> 00:11:30,300
It's intensely claustrophobic.

196
00:11:31,120 --> 00:11:31,300
Yeah.

197
00:11:31,300 --> 00:11:36,820
The control room is bathed in a cold, spectral, sourceless green light.

198
00:11:37,460 --> 00:11:41,480
It's the kind of illumination that makes humans look sickly and alien.

199
00:11:42,560 --> 00:11:49,260
Faces are lit sharply from the consoles below, casting unnatural shadows upward onto the ceiling.

200
00:11:49,360 --> 00:11:50,400
Very unsettling.

201
00:11:50,400 --> 00:12:03,580
And outside the thick viewports, in the absolute black of space, there are terrifying light distortions, massive ripples of kinetic force pounding against the station's defensive grid.

202
00:12:04,160 --> 00:12:05,540
The assault is overwhelming.

203
00:12:06,100 --> 00:12:06,280
Right.

204
00:12:06,380 --> 00:12:07,520
Klaxons are screaming.

205
00:12:07,940 --> 00:12:11,900
Red warning indicators are multiplying across every surface like a virus.

206
00:12:12,300 --> 00:12:13,920
It's total signal saturation.

207
00:12:14,240 --> 00:12:18,380
Yet inside that room, the human operators are disturbingly calm.

208
00:12:18,460 --> 00:12:19,600
It's so weird.

209
00:12:19,600 --> 00:12:30,040
The station's shields are visibly failing, hull breaches are imminent, but the commanding officer simply paces behind the consoles, issuing precise, unemotional orders.

210
00:12:30,840 --> 00:12:33,120
Signal saturation sectors 2 through 5.

211
00:12:33,740 --> 00:12:34,740
Reroot to auxiliary.

212
00:12:35,600 --> 00:12:36,520
There is no panic.

213
00:12:36,640 --> 00:12:37,740
There is only procedure.

214
00:12:38,200 --> 00:12:46,140
Lumen is staring at his tactical display, and the data inputs are flooding the screen faster than the human eye can track.

215
00:12:46,280 --> 00:12:48,460
It's a complete sensory overload.

216
00:12:48,460 --> 00:12:48,980
Right.

217
00:12:48,980 --> 00:12:52,160
But the text makes a critical distinction here.

218
00:12:52,960 --> 00:12:55,580
Lumen isn't paralyzed by the fear of death.

219
00:12:55,920 --> 00:12:56,860
No, not at all.

220
00:12:56,940 --> 00:12:59,960
He is paralyzed by the sheer volume of complexity.

221
00:13:00,700 --> 00:13:09,220
The defense grid's operation has exponentially exceeded the cognitive capacity of any single human observer inside the room.

222
00:13:09,580 --> 00:13:17,220
And this is where we encounter a foundational pillar of modern systems theory, the concept of complexity reduction.

223
00:13:17,220 --> 00:13:17,620
Right.

224
00:13:17,900 --> 00:13:18,960
Let's talk about that.

225
00:13:18,980 --> 00:13:48,980


226
00:13:48,980 --> 00:13:50,900
The system didn't break down into chaos.

227
00:13:50,900 --> 00:13:56,720
Under immense pressure, it revealed what the script calls a geometry of fragmentation.

228
00:13:56,720 --> 00:14:02,420
The architecture of the system becomes legible precisely as it shatters.

229
00:14:02,420 --> 00:14:08,120
The system had simply exceeded the capacity of any single observer.

230
00:14:08,120 --> 00:14:25,240
Even while the station is being torn apart, every single individual element, every subroutine, every automated power reroute, every physical console is still faithfully executing its own internal logic.

231
00:14:25,240 --> 00:14:25,680
Right.

232
00:14:25,680 --> 00:14:31,120
The whole is collapsing, but each element followed its own logic as the whole came apart.

233
00:14:31,120 --> 00:14:36,920
I just remember the thousands of high-frequency trading bots are executing their programming flawlessly.

234
00:14:37,420 --> 00:14:42,080
The system is just operating at a scale and speed that humans can't process.

235
00:14:42,220 --> 00:14:42,720
Exactly.

236
00:14:43,260 --> 00:14:45,900
The system is just doing what it's built to do.

237
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:46,200
Yeah.

238
00:14:46,200 --> 00:14:52,480
But there's a vital philosophical distinction we need to make to fully grasp Luhmann's point here.

239
00:14:52,520 --> 00:14:52,780
Okay.

240
00:14:52,940 --> 00:14:53,460
What is it?

241
00:14:53,460 --> 00:15:05,780
Algorithmic trading bots, no matter how complex, were ultimately programmed by human beings to achieve a specific human goal generating financial profit.

242
00:15:05,980 --> 00:15:06,360
Right.

243
00:15:07,080 --> 00:15:11,160
Luhmann is arguing something far more extreme about societal systems.

244
00:15:11,160 --> 00:15:18,160
He argues that systems like the economy or the legal structure do not possess human goals whatsoever.

245
00:15:19,040 --> 00:15:19,640
Wow.

246
00:15:20,120 --> 00:15:23,840
They are autonomous entities that use us to continue their own communication.

247
00:15:24,200 --> 00:15:24,400
Yeah.

248
00:15:24,800 --> 00:15:30,820
The shield control system during the attack isn't trying to save the lives of the colonists out of a sense of moral duty.

249
00:15:30,960 --> 00:15:31,540
It's not.

250
00:15:31,820 --> 00:15:32,100
No.

251
00:15:32,620 --> 00:15:39,540
It is simply processing the binary code of shield integrity holding versus shield integrity failing.

252
00:15:39,540 --> 00:15:41,540
That is a terrifying distinction.

253
00:15:41,780 --> 00:15:42,140
It is.

254
00:15:42,480 --> 00:15:46,740
And as the station fails, what does 16-year-old Luhmann do?

255
00:15:47,880 --> 00:15:48,760
He doesn't pray.

256
00:15:49,480 --> 00:15:50,220
He doesn't panic.

257
00:15:50,560 --> 00:16:00,640
He pulls a small, crumpled scrap of paper from his uniform pocket, finds a pen, and begins taking meticulous notes on the failure cascade on his screen,

258
00:16:01,120 --> 00:16:05,860
noting numbers and arrows, the very beginning of his famous system.

259
00:16:06,040 --> 00:16:08,360
He becomes the ultimate detached observer.

260
00:16:08,360 --> 00:16:08,880
Yeah.

261
00:16:09,380 --> 00:16:13,260
And the station does survive the assault, though deeply scarred.

262
00:16:13,560 --> 00:16:14,080
Barely.

263
00:16:14,280 --> 00:16:14,540
Right.

264
00:16:14,760 --> 00:16:21,720
Or at least Luhmann survives, because our next glimpse of him occurs later, living in a gray, uniform detention vessel.

265
00:16:22,040 --> 00:16:24,340
The environment shifts radically again.

266
00:16:25,200 --> 00:16:34,280
We leave the intense, chaotic green glow of the combat control room and enter a space defined by absolute, timeless monotony.

267
00:16:34,320 --> 00:16:35,560
A completely different feel.

268
00:16:35,560 --> 00:16:35,920
Yeah.

269
00:16:36,340 --> 00:16:39,300
The overhead lighting is a flat, institutional gray.

270
00:16:39,940 --> 00:16:41,780
It doesn't mimic a day-night cycle.

271
00:16:42,120 --> 00:16:46,940
The lights simply click on and off according to a rigid, arbitrary administrative schedule.

272
00:16:46,940 --> 00:16:54,840
And the detention hold sequence shows how a function, in this case, guarding prisoners, is entirely indifferent to its personnel.

273
00:16:55,300 --> 00:16:58,220
Luhmann observes that the individual guards rotate.

274
00:16:58,760 --> 00:16:59,820
The faces change.

275
00:16:59,820 --> 00:17:03,840
But the procedure of guarding remains exactly the same.

276
00:17:03,840 --> 00:17:09,880
The scanning of the ID badges, the mechanical clack of the locks, it's identical.

277
00:17:10,520 --> 00:17:14,740
The function of the prison is entirely indifferent to the people executing the function.

278
00:17:15,520 --> 00:17:21,720
And in this bleak space, Luhmann begins mapping a cross-reference system.

279
00:17:21,820 --> 00:17:22,720
With a ration card.

280
00:17:22,720 --> 00:17:23,020
Yes.

281
00:17:23,360 --> 00:17:25,580
He uses the back of a ration card.

282
00:17:25,640 --> 00:17:25,880
Right.

283
00:17:26,240 --> 00:17:33,360
He sits there observing a fellow prisoner designated as the librarian who has this battered physical ledger.

284
00:17:34,260 --> 00:17:36,700
Luhmann ignores the books and the people.

285
00:17:36,880 --> 00:17:39,220
He just zeroes in on the ledger, taking notes.

286
00:17:39,220 --> 00:17:48,540
This realization in the detention hold that systems survive their own personnel leads directly into Luhmann's career in colonial administration.

287
00:17:48,920 --> 00:17:49,140
Right.

288
00:17:49,360 --> 00:17:50,880
The next phase of his life.

289
00:17:51,060 --> 00:17:51,320
Yeah.

290
00:17:51,560 --> 00:17:54,900
Where he sees this indifference as a feature, not a bug.

291
00:17:55,100 --> 00:17:57,120
Let's jump into the 2420s.

292
00:17:57,200 --> 00:17:57,420
Yeah.

293
00:17:57,580 --> 00:17:59,860
Years 2422 to 2432.

294
00:18:00,800 --> 00:18:04,560
Luhmann spends an entire decade working in colonial administration.

295
00:18:04,560 --> 00:18:09,220
Visually, the narrative shifts to reflect this bureaucracy.

296
00:18:09,460 --> 00:18:09,840
It does.

297
00:18:09,960 --> 00:18:13,640
We get this warm, practical light, but static wide shots.

298
00:18:13,660 --> 00:18:13,960
Right.

299
00:18:14,200 --> 00:18:16,700
The visual framing is deeply deliberate.

300
00:18:16,700 --> 00:18:24,420
As the narrative explicitly states, the institution contains the people.

301
00:18:25,320 --> 00:18:27,460
The people execute the institution.

302
00:18:27,540 --> 00:18:29,120
Oh, that's such a great line.

303
00:18:29,120 --> 00:18:36,560
By locking the camera down, the director emphasizes the rigid, unmoving borders of the bureaucratic environment.

304
00:18:37,320 --> 00:18:39,800
The humans merely pass through the frame.

305
00:18:39,920 --> 00:18:45,120
And we see Luhmann sitting at a desk processing planetary colonization permits.

306
00:18:45,960 --> 00:18:46,280
Yes.

307
00:18:46,600 --> 00:18:49,140
And there's this auditory rhythm to the work.

308
00:18:49,840 --> 00:18:50,700
The stamp falls.

309
00:18:51,140 --> 00:18:51,800
Falls again.

310
00:18:52,240 --> 00:18:52,800
Falls again.

311
00:18:52,900 --> 00:18:56,500
The rhythm of it, mechanical, indifferent, continuous.

312
00:18:56,500 --> 00:18:58,160
It doesn't matter who holds the stamp.

313
00:18:58,280 --> 00:18:59,640
The stamp falls all the same.

314
00:18:59,820 --> 00:19:00,140
Exactly.

315
00:19:00,680 --> 00:19:05,940
He watches a registrar explain that forms must be completed in an exact sequence.

316
00:19:06,660 --> 00:19:11,640
The registrar says, the system maintains itself because we follow the procedures.

317
00:19:11,960 --> 00:19:13,020
And Luhmann's response.

318
00:19:13,360 --> 00:19:16,480
Luhmann agrees quietly, adding, that's what I mean.

319
00:19:16,680 --> 00:19:20,000
Because this is the core of procedural self-maintenance.

320
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:26,440
The bureaucracy is a living organism that uses humans simply to sustain its own communication loop.

321
00:19:26,860 --> 00:19:31,640
I mean, how many times have you been trapped in red tape at the DMV or a corporate HR department?

322
00:19:31,760 --> 00:19:32,520
Too many times.

323
00:19:32,780 --> 00:19:33,080
Right.

324
00:19:33,480 --> 00:19:37,120
You're frustrated because the employee won't just use common sense.

325
00:19:37,240 --> 00:19:40,120
You're begging them to just look at the reality of the situation.

326
00:19:40,440 --> 00:19:43,120
And they just say, sorry, the system won't allow it.

327
00:19:43,280 --> 00:19:43,740
Exactly.

328
00:19:43,740 --> 00:19:52,940
While we experience this as a maddening lack of empathy, Luhmann observed it as a brilliant survival mechanism.

329
00:19:53,300 --> 00:19:54,620
That's the paradigm shift.

330
00:19:54,860 --> 00:19:55,100
Yeah.

331
00:19:55,360 --> 00:20:00,420
If the system relied on human empathy or individual logic, it would collapse.

332
00:20:01,080 --> 00:20:05,360
We have to delve into Luhmann's concept of binary coding to understand why.

333
00:20:05,460 --> 00:20:06,420
Okay, let's do it.

334
00:20:06,420 --> 00:20:14,620
According to his theory, every social system operates on a specific, mutually exclusive binary code.

335
00:20:15,340 --> 00:20:20,460
The legal system operates solely on the code of legal versus illegal.

336
00:20:20,920 --> 00:20:24,700
The economic system operates on payment versus non-payment.

337
00:20:24,920 --> 00:20:24,960
Right.

338
00:20:25,360 --> 00:20:31,180
The administrative bureaucracy operates on the code of procedurally correct versus procedurally incorrect.

339
00:20:31,180 --> 00:20:37,540
It does not possess a code for moral versus immoral or empathetic versus cruel.

340
00:20:37,800 --> 00:20:38,720
It just doesn't compute.

341
00:20:39,060 --> 00:20:39,480
Exactly.

342
00:20:40,100 --> 00:20:45,200
If the administrative system suddenly allowed clerks to make exceptions based on empathy,

343
00:20:45,760 --> 00:20:48,180
the boundary of the system would instantly dissolve.

344
00:20:48,580 --> 00:20:52,880
It would be overwhelmed by the infinite complexity of the human environment,

345
00:20:53,160 --> 00:20:56,700
and the entire bureaucratic structure would collapse.

346
00:20:56,700 --> 00:21:02,180
It survives because it's utterly deaf to individual human pleading.

347
00:21:02,860 --> 00:21:09,420
And during all this, Luhmann's desk begins accumulating small cards with numbers and arrows,

348
00:21:10,060 --> 00:21:12,200
completely ignored by his colleagues.

349
00:21:12,460 --> 00:21:13,980
He's quietly building his mirror.

350
00:21:14,340 --> 00:21:14,580
Yeah.

351
00:21:15,200 --> 00:21:23,300
But seeing human systems as cold in different machines is a radical and somewhat unsettling perspective.

352
00:21:23,620 --> 00:21:24,420
Very much so.

353
00:21:24,420 --> 00:21:28,020
So when Luhmann tries to explain this to the academic elite,

354
00:21:28,160 --> 00:21:31,200
he immediately runs into ideological brick walls.

355
00:21:31,340 --> 00:21:32,380
The academic clashes.

356
00:21:32,740 --> 00:21:33,020
Right.

357
00:21:33,480 --> 00:21:36,600
Luhmann clashes with two major academic figures,

358
00:21:37,020 --> 00:21:39,680
the director at Harvard Station in 2432

359
00:21:39,680 --> 00:21:44,660
and the critical theorist at the Frankfurt Institute in 2439.

360
00:21:45,120 --> 00:21:46,380
Let's start with Harvard Station.

361
00:21:46,820 --> 00:21:50,600
The author's use of environmental storytelling here is phenomenal.

362
00:21:50,780 --> 00:21:51,820
It's so good.

363
00:21:51,820 --> 00:21:57,700
Harvard is bathed in warm, intentional light, suggesting endorsement.

364
00:21:58,480 --> 00:22:03,860
It is the physical manifestation of intellectual comfort and established authority.

365
00:22:04,020 --> 00:22:04,340
Right.

366
00:22:05,020 --> 00:22:09,400
And the director believes systems survive through integration.

367
00:22:09,940 --> 00:22:13,200
The idea that parts coordinate for shared values.

368
00:22:13,200 --> 00:22:15,420
Like a harmonious functionalist view.

369
00:22:15,420 --> 00:22:16,020
Exactly.

370
00:22:16,660 --> 00:22:19,860
But Luhmann argues they survive through closure and differentiation.

371
00:22:20,640 --> 00:22:22,600
The parts continue regardless of each other.

372
00:22:22,740 --> 00:22:22,960
Right.

373
00:22:23,180 --> 00:22:27,080
They built impenetrable boundaries to protect their internal communication.

374
00:22:27,420 --> 00:22:27,760
Yes.

375
00:22:28,360 --> 00:22:32,460
But that's a polite disagreement compared to the Frankfurt Institute in 2439.

376
00:22:32,700 --> 00:22:33,300
Oh, yeah.

377
00:22:33,520 --> 00:22:35,840
This is where things get really heated.

378
00:22:36,200 --> 00:22:42,220
The Frankfurt Dinner Party continues entirely indifferent to the passionate argument happening at the table.

379
00:22:42,720 --> 00:22:44,740
It's a dimly lit, smoky room.

380
00:22:44,740 --> 00:22:48,120
And he's seated across from the critical theorist.

381
00:22:48,380 --> 00:22:48,640
Yes.

382
00:22:49,300 --> 00:22:53,080
And the critical theorist demands sociology be normative.

383
00:22:54,060 --> 00:22:58,480
They demand he criticize society for inequality and environmental destruction.

384
00:22:58,740 --> 00:23:02,080
Now, I want to pause here for a second just to be clear to our listeners.

385
00:23:02,800 --> 00:23:05,520
We are strictly maintaining neutrality here.

386
00:23:05,880 --> 00:23:11,600
We are not taking any sides on the political or social issues mentioned by the critical theorist.

387
00:23:11,640 --> 00:23:11,880
Right.

388
00:23:11,960 --> 00:23:12,340
Absolutely.

389
00:23:12,340 --> 00:23:27,960
We are simply exploring the philosophical debate presented in the text, the clash between normative criticism, which is how things ought to be, and pure descriptive sociology, which is how things are.

390
00:23:28,080 --> 00:23:30,000
We are not endorsing either side.

391
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:30,520
Exactly.

392
00:23:30,520 --> 00:23:30,560
Exactly.

393
00:23:30,700 --> 00:23:31,940
It's a theoretical debate.

394
00:23:32,580 --> 00:23:37,140
And in this debate, Luhmann demands pure description for accuracy.

395
00:23:38,400 --> 00:23:42,900
He argues there is no position outside the system from which to judge it.

396
00:23:43,400 --> 00:23:43,520
Right.

397
00:23:43,700 --> 00:23:48,420
If we connect this to the bigger picture, this is Luhmann's epistemology of honesty.

398
00:23:48,420 --> 00:23:53,260
If society is everything, you can't step outside it to critique it.

399
00:23:53,820 --> 00:23:55,820
But here's where it gets really interesting.

400
00:23:56,100 --> 00:24:00,460
And I want to push back on Luhmann's view here, kind of on behalf of the listener.

401
00:24:00,780 --> 00:24:01,320
Go for it.

402
00:24:01,540 --> 00:24:04,260
Isn't pure description just a cop-out?

403
00:24:04,600 --> 00:24:05,080
How do you mean?

404
00:24:05,340 --> 00:24:06,300
Well, think about it.

405
00:24:06,460 --> 00:24:11,240
If a ship is sinking, purely describing the water level feels useless.

406
00:24:11,820 --> 00:24:13,200
You don't need a describer.

407
00:24:13,280 --> 00:24:14,680
You need someone patching the hole.

408
00:24:15,040 --> 00:24:17,340
That's exactly what the critical theorist feels.

409
00:24:17,340 --> 00:24:20,620
It's the difference between a mechanic and a driving instructor.

410
00:24:21,820 --> 00:24:26,340
The critical theorist wants to teach society how to drive safely, right?

411
00:24:27,200 --> 00:24:31,300
Luhmann is the mechanic who just wants to mack exactly how the engine runs,

412
00:24:31,460 --> 00:24:34,520
even if the car is currently speeding toward a cliff.

413
00:24:34,940 --> 00:24:36,200
That's a perfect analogy.

414
00:24:36,440 --> 00:24:39,620
And the text quotes this exchange directly.

415
00:24:39,780 --> 00:24:43,020
The theorist says, that's a politics of resignation.

416
00:24:43,020 --> 00:24:47,500
And Luhmann replies, it's an epistemology of honesty.

417
00:24:48,400 --> 00:24:50,040
It's such a stark divide.

418
00:24:50,120 --> 00:24:50,840
It really is.

419
00:24:50,980 --> 00:24:51,120
Yeah.

420
00:24:51,240 --> 00:24:56,060
Because Luhmann believes you can't step outside the system of society to analyze it.

421
00:24:56,460 --> 00:25:02,720
He realizes the only way to truly map it is to build a complex, closed system of his own.

422
00:25:02,720 --> 00:25:05,600
Which brings us to the ultimate system.

423
00:25:06,360 --> 00:25:07,300
The Zettelkasten.

424
00:25:07,520 --> 00:25:07,940
Yes.

425
00:25:07,940 --> 00:25:11,160
So, we are at the Beelfeld Academy.

426
00:25:11,360 --> 00:25:12,580
The year is 2440.

427
00:25:12,720 --> 00:25:14,340
Luhmann is 40 years old.

428
00:25:14,380 --> 00:25:14,700
Right.

429
00:25:15,220 --> 00:25:20,100
And he proposes a 30-year research project to map the theory of modern society.

430
00:25:20,100 --> 00:25:24,600
And his budget requirement, no costs.

431
00:25:25,060 --> 00:25:27,780
Which is just, I mean, it's such an audacious claim.

432
00:25:28,100 --> 00:25:28,540
I know.

433
00:25:28,860 --> 00:25:30,220
Just a desk and paper.

434
00:25:31,040 --> 00:25:37,260
And over decades, his slip box system grows from one wooden box to 60,000 cards.

435
00:25:37,520 --> 00:25:42,740
And finally, to 90,000 cards, taking over his entire office.

436
00:25:43,120 --> 00:25:45,140
This raises an important question.

437
00:25:45,460 --> 00:25:48,800
How does a pile of paper become a communication partner?

438
00:25:48,800 --> 00:25:50,140
Yeah, how does that work?

439
00:25:50,820 --> 00:25:56,200
By relying purely on relations and cross-references, that geometry of reference we saw earlier,

440
00:25:57,000 --> 00:26:02,040
the Zettelkasten stops being a storage container and becomes an active system.

441
00:26:02,160 --> 00:26:02,440
Right.

442
00:26:02,540 --> 00:26:04,980
Because he didn't use a top-down categorization.

443
00:26:05,240 --> 00:26:07,360
He used this alphanumeric branching.

444
00:26:07,540 --> 00:26:09,880
1A connects to 1A1 and so on.

445
00:26:10,220 --> 00:26:10,820
Exactly.

446
00:26:11,420 --> 00:26:13,840
And the script visualizes this beautifully.

447
00:26:13,840 --> 00:26:20,940
As the cards multiply, going from contained boxes to stacks outside the boxes, to drawers

448
00:26:20,940 --> 00:26:26,500
extending to every wall, erasing the distinction between container and contents, the light in

449
00:26:26,500 --> 00:26:27,620
the room actually changes.

450
00:26:27,800 --> 00:26:28,240
Wow.

451
00:26:28,420 --> 00:26:33,040
The system generates its own atmosphere, just like the fermentation tanks and the shield

452
00:26:33,040 --> 00:26:33,820
consoles did.

453
00:26:34,140 --> 00:26:35,080
That is so cool.

454
00:26:35,080 --> 00:26:40,320
And when a colleague asks if he can find anything in it, Lumen says it's less like finding something

455
00:26:40,320 --> 00:26:43,440
and more like receiving a reply from the system.

456
00:26:43,860 --> 00:26:47,900
The network became so complex, it generated emergent insights.

457
00:26:48,120 --> 00:26:48,340
Yeah.

458
00:26:48,700 --> 00:26:51,900
But of course, this level of complexity comes with a catch.

459
00:26:52,480 --> 00:26:53,360
Oh yes, it does.

460
00:26:53,540 --> 00:27:00,580
A colleague notes that his prose, his actual writing, is deliberately impenetrable.

461
00:27:00,780 --> 00:27:03,220
It is notoriously difficult to read.

462
00:27:03,220 --> 00:27:03,700
Yeah.

463
00:27:04,120 --> 00:27:05,920
I have to laugh at his defense, though.

464
00:27:06,540 --> 00:27:12,400
Lumen defends it by saying, comprehension that arrives too quickly produces only sophisticated

465
00:27:12,400 --> 00:27:13,340
misunderstanding.

466
00:27:13,920 --> 00:27:16,880
It sounds arrogant, but there's a profound truth there.

467
00:27:17,060 --> 00:27:17,880
There really is.

468
00:27:17,920 --> 00:27:22,120
It's like reading a complex legal contract versus a tweet.

469
00:27:22,300 --> 00:27:22,920
Oh, absolutely.

470
00:27:23,200 --> 00:27:25,400
A tweet is instantly comprehensible.

471
00:27:25,480 --> 00:27:26,740
Yeah, you read it in a second.

472
00:27:26,820 --> 00:27:32,340
But it often strips away all nuance leading to outrage, which is essentially misunderstanding.

473
00:27:32,340 --> 00:27:40,400
The dense legal contract, or Lumen's writing, forces you to slow down and map the actual

474
00:27:40,400 --> 00:27:42,000
boundaries of the agreement.

475
00:27:42,400 --> 00:27:44,780
It acts as a speed bump for human cognition.

476
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:45,560
Exactly.

477
00:27:45,880 --> 00:27:47,040
You can't take shortcuts.

478
00:27:47,200 --> 00:27:51,940
And this ability to see profound structural relations where others just see a massive,

479
00:27:52,360 --> 00:27:57,560
confusing pile of data brings us to Lumen's final revelation about the nature of the universe.

480
00:27:57,560 --> 00:28:00,840
Section 6, signal and noise.

481
00:28:01,300 --> 00:28:01,660
Yes.

482
00:28:02,120 --> 00:28:04,500
We jump to the year 2455.

483
00:28:05,520 --> 00:28:08,700
We are in a signal analysis lab on the outer station.

484
00:28:09,120 --> 00:28:12,920
The lighting here is this clinical blue-white.

485
00:28:13,080 --> 00:28:13,940
Very sterile.

486
00:28:13,940 --> 00:28:21,660
And an analyst is looking at a deep space waveform from the Ankira peripheral station.

487
00:28:23,580 --> 00:28:29,940
And the analyst just dismisses it as noise because it doesn't match known protocols.

488
00:28:30,740 --> 00:28:31,540
But Lumen is there.

489
00:28:31,900 --> 00:28:32,560
Lumen is there.

490
00:28:32,680 --> 00:28:37,660
And he replies, not matching a protocol isn't the same as having no structure.

491
00:28:38,080 --> 00:28:41,600
That line just, it carries so much philosophical weight.

492
00:28:41,760 --> 00:28:42,520
It really does.

493
00:28:42,800 --> 00:28:43,860
Break that down for us.

494
00:28:44,180 --> 00:28:49,340
Well, human beings arrogantly define anything we don't immediately understand as noise.

495
00:28:49,620 --> 00:28:49,760
Right.

496
00:28:50,000 --> 00:28:54,740
But Lumen's entire life was about looking at the noise, the bureaucracy, the complex data,

497
00:28:54,880 --> 00:28:58,040
the societal failure, and finding the underlying structure.

498
00:28:58,480 --> 00:29:02,380
He refused to believe it was meaningless just because our protocols couldn't decode it yet.

499
00:29:02,540 --> 00:29:03,860
That's incredibly powerful.

500
00:29:03,860 --> 00:29:08,320
And then the script ends in 2464, back where we started.

501
00:29:08,640 --> 00:29:10,500
Back at the Lunenberg fermentation plant.

502
00:29:10,680 --> 00:29:10,960
Yes.

503
00:29:10,960 --> 00:29:17,080
64-year-old Lumen watches the gauge stabilize, just like he did at age 10.

504
00:29:17,080 --> 00:29:20,900
And the continuous hum of the system persists.

505
00:29:20,900 --> 00:29:24,200
It's not an explosion or a space battle.

506
00:29:24,200 --> 00:29:31,100
The emotional climax is just him recognizing the eternal hum of self-maintaining systems.

507
00:29:31,240 --> 00:29:34,640
Returning to that green-brown, organic hum.

508
00:29:34,640 --> 00:29:35,320
Yeah.

509
00:29:35,320 --> 00:29:39,100
And then the script concludes with historical facts.

510
00:29:39,100 --> 00:29:55,460
The real Nicholas Lumen, 1927 to 1998, wrote 70 books, 400 articles, digitized his 90,000-card Zettelkasten, and published his magnum opus,

511
00:29:55,460 --> 00:29:59,660
Die Gesellschaft der Gesellschaft, the Society of Society.

512
00:30:00,060 --> 00:30:00,980
It's just brilliant.

513
00:30:01,040 --> 00:30:02,240
So what does this all mean?

514
00:30:02,240 --> 00:30:14,700
I mean, I marvel at the format of the source text, pointing out that this entire 25th century space opera was actually a brilliantly disguised biography of a real 20th century German sociologist.

515
00:30:14,700 --> 00:30:16,620
It's an incredible structural choice.

516
00:30:16,620 --> 00:30:21,260
It's like using a sci-fi telescope to look backwards at a 1990s academic.

517
00:30:21,860 --> 00:30:32,940
The sci-fi setting strips away our modern biases, forcing us to look at the structure of Lumen's thought, rather than getting bogged down in the biographical minutia of 20th century Germany.

518
00:30:33,480 --> 00:30:33,820
Yes.

519
00:30:34,260 --> 00:30:36,320
We aren't distracted by the history.

520
00:30:36,620 --> 00:30:38,460
We just see the communication.

521
00:30:38,700 --> 00:30:39,360
We hear the hum.

522
00:30:39,620 --> 00:30:40,120
Exactly.

523
00:30:40,400 --> 00:30:44,520
So let's recap this massive journey we've been on.

524
00:30:44,620 --> 00:30:45,500
It's been quite the ride.

525
00:30:45,500 --> 00:30:58,500
From watching biomass tanks, to mapping failing space stations, to defending an epistemology of honesty, to building a 90,000-card system that talks back.

526
00:30:58,600 --> 00:30:59,880
We've covered a lot of ground.

527
00:31:00,080 --> 00:31:01,140
We really have.

528
00:31:01,220 --> 00:31:11,360
We've learned that systems are indifferent, they maintain themselves through closure, and they communicate beyond the capacity of any single human.

529
00:31:11,540 --> 00:31:12,640
They outlast us all.

530
00:31:12,640 --> 00:31:13,080
Yeah.

531
00:31:13,300 --> 00:31:16,300
So I want to connect this back to you, the listener.

532
00:31:16,520 --> 00:31:17,020
Good idea.

533
00:31:17,400 --> 00:31:29,000
The next time you find yourself frustrated by a rigid bureaucracy, a confusing algorithm, or a massive institution that seems to ignore common sense, remember Lumen?

534
00:31:29,220 --> 00:31:30,260
Try stepping back.

535
00:31:30,380 --> 00:31:30,880
Exactly.

536
00:31:31,100 --> 00:31:32,020
Don't look at the people.

537
00:31:32,200 --> 00:31:33,180
Look at the communication.

538
00:31:33,440 --> 00:31:34,300
Look at the structure.

539
00:31:34,600 --> 00:31:37,140
Because that's where the real machinery is operating.

540
00:31:37,380 --> 00:31:37,720
Right.

541
00:31:37,720 --> 00:31:43,740
And, you know, I want to leave everyone with one final kind of haunting question to chew on.

542
00:31:43,840 --> 00:31:45,540
Oh, I like a provocative thought.

543
00:31:45,740 --> 00:31:46,640
Lay it on us.

544
00:31:47,260 --> 00:32:00,500
If Lumen is right, if society is truly a closed system made entirely of communication and not of people, then what happens to you when you disconnect?

545
00:32:00,860 --> 00:32:01,640
Oh, wow.

546
00:32:01,640 --> 00:32:02,560
Think about it.

547
00:32:02,820 --> 00:32:11,580
When you turn off your phone, close your mouth, and sit in total silence, do you temporarily cease to exist as a part of society?

548
00:32:11,740 --> 00:32:14,020
That is, I mean, that really sticks with you.

549
00:32:14,140 --> 00:32:16,360
Are you even there if you aren't communicating?

550
00:32:16,740 --> 00:32:17,140
Exactly.

551
00:32:17,640 --> 00:32:17,940
Yeah.

552
00:32:17,940 --> 00:32:18,840
Something to think about.

553
00:32:18,980 --> 00:32:23,320
Well, on that existential note, thank you all for joining us on this deep dive.

554
00:32:23,440 --> 00:32:24,060
It's been a pleasure.

555
00:32:24,260 --> 00:32:25,000
See you next time.

556
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:54,980
See you next time.

